        "number": 3,
        "title": "The blessing pronounced — covenant content in a fraudulent moment",
        "range": "27:18-29",
        "excerpt": "'See, the smell of my son is like the smell of a field which the LORD has blessed; now may God give you of the dew of heaven, and of the fatness of the earth... May peoples serve you, and nations bow down to you.'",
        "body": "The scene of the actual blessing is the chapter's theological core. Jacob approaches three times (27:18, 21, 25) before Isaac finally pronounces. Each approach is an opportunity for exposure: Isaac questions the timing (27:20), registers the voice-anomaly (27:22), asks the identity question directly (27:24). Each time Jacob either lies or the disguise holds. The scene is constructed to maximize the reader's discomfort — we watch the covenant blessing approach, delivered in a lie.\n\nYet when Isaac speaks (27:27–29), he speaks precisely. The content of the blessing is structurally identical to the Abrahamic promises. 'Dew of heaven and the fatness of the earth' echoes the land-promise given to Abraham in 12:7 and 13:15. 'Peoples serve you, nations bow down to you' echoes the seed-promise of 22:17–18. 'Cursed be those who curse you, blessed be those who bless you' is verbatim from 12:3. Isaac does not know he is speaking to Jacob — but the words he has been given to speak, drawn from decades of inhabiting the Abrahamic covenant, are the exact words that belong to the man God designated. Douglas Moo, commenting on Hebrews 11:20 (which credits Isaac for blessing 'by faith'), notes that Isaac's faith is not in the act of blessing Jacob — of which he was ignorant — but in the substance of the covenant promises he transmits, which he believed God would fulfill.\n\nThe meal Isaac eats before the blessing (27:25) deserves attention. The narrative detail that Isaac ate, drank wine, kissed Jacob, and smelled his garments before blessing him suggests a covenant ratification ceremony — the meal seals the transfer. This is not superstition; it is the ancient Near Eastern covenantal logic in which shared food establishes shared standing. The tragedy is that the man being received into covenant fellowship is not who Isaac thinks he is — and yet, theologically, he is exactly who the blessing must reach.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yehovah barakh* (which the LORD has blessed, 27:27) — the divine name in the blessing formula ties the transfer directly to covenant history, not merely to patriarchal wish. *Gevir* (master, 27:29) — lord, master; the same term appears in 27:37, confirming the transfer is legally complete. *Shachah* (bow down) is the standard term for prostration before a superior — the blessing forecasts political submission, not merely fraternal respect."
